<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Starts Massive Repair Work After Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Saturday started to repair
power stations, roads and bridges destroyed in the 10-hour Israeli
air strike on the country two days ago.
</P>
<P>
Army engineering units were installing iron bridges and
building alternative side roads near the two bridges linking
Beirut and southern Lebanon that were destroyed, said
Secretary-General of Lebanon's Higher Relief Council Liwa Ruad
after an emergency meeting chaired by Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
The reconstruction of destroyed bridges will complete in two
months, he said.
</P>
<P>
But, what usually is an hour-long drive now will stretch three
or four hours as cars will have to take detours along narrow and
winding mountain roads amid snarled traffic.
</P>
<P>
Ruad said that within 10 days, electricity supply in Beirut
and its environments will increase from the current 2 hours daily
to 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
The full restorage of power supply will need a period of time,
he said, without giving a specific date.
</P>
<P>
Israel launched a 10-hour aerial blitz on Lebanon's
infrastructure Thursday night to retaliate an earlier cross-border
attacks by guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, which is
fighting to oust Israeli troops out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Eight Lebanese, most of them civil defense workers, were
killed and 64 others wounded in the Israeli offensive, the
biggest since the 1996 Israeli "Grapes of Wrath" operation which
killed at least 200 people, most of whom are civilians.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah said its Katyusha rockets, which killed two
Israelis, served as a response to the wounding of a Lebanese
woman by the Israeli shelling in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Officials have estimated at 30 million U.S. dollars the damage
to the two destroyed power stations lying on a hill overlooking
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, which is suffering the worst economic recession with
a huge debt of over 18 billion dollars since it launched a massive
reconstruction process, has already secured offers for help.
</P>
<P>
Billionaire Saudi Prince Walid bin Talal has offered to foot
the bill of rebuilding the power stations while Syria offered
emergency electricity supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
