<HEADLINE> Tanzanian First Speaker Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian first Speaker of
the parliament since independence in 1961 from the British
colonial rule, Chief Adam Sapi Mkwawa, died of illness Friday at
the age of 79.
</P>
<P>
Mkwawa, one of Tanzania's most popular statesmen and
legislators, passed away Friday night at the Muhimbili Medical
Center in Dar es Salaam after a ten-day battle with high blood
pressure, a statement by the National Assembly (the parliament),
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Mkwawa succeeded his father Chief Sapi Mkwawa as a chief
of the Hehe Tribe in central Iringa region in 1940 and held the
position till 1962.
</P>
<P>
From November 27, 1962, the statement said, Mkwawa had been
served as the speaker of the first National Assembly until 1973
when he became a minister of State for Capital Development.
</P>
<P>
He came back to the parliament again in 1975 as the speaker
until his retirement.
</P>
<P>
He was survived by a widow and ten children.
</P>
<P>
His brother Edmundi said that Mkwawa was planned to be buried
at his home village Karenga in Iringa Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials, including President Benjamin Mkapa, were
expected to pay their last respect to Mkwawa Monday afternoon at
his residence in Oysterbay, Dar es Salaam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
