<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Russia's 1999 Inflation to Hit 85 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian First Deputy Prime Minister
Viktor Khristenko warned Saturday that the country's inflation may
amount to 85 percent by the end of the year and the ruble exchange
rate could slide to 30 against the U.S. dollar if it fails to
resolve its debt problem.
</P>
<P>
"The government's objective is to work with creditors,"
Khristenko said while touring Saratov, a city 1,500 kilometers
southeast of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
"We have no right for illusions that Russia can borrow new
credits," the Interfax news agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, or lower house of parliament, has passed 18 of
31 measures prescribed by the International Monetary Fund as part
of a reform program that Russia must fulfill to unlock 4.5 billion
dollars in loans to avoid an embarrassing default on earlier debts
to the fund.
</P>
<P>
An IMF mission is scheduled to come to Moscow next Monday to
review Russia's standing.
</P>
<P>
Khristenko said the cabinet "is not making new debts but tries
to refinance the old ones" at the current talks with international
financial institutions."
</P>
<P>
Given a positive settlement of the debt issue, Russia's
industrial output could grow 3.5 percent by the end of the year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, Russia's economy "seems stable" as
industrial production went up 1.5 percent in the first five months
of the year, Khristenko said.
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet does not aim to draw up new long-term
programs for Russia's socioeconomic development in the next 10 to
15 years, but rather, it will implement the "already written"
ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Finance Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said Saturday it
would not resort to Central Bank loans for meeting foreign debt
payments in the second half of the year if the IMF in late July
approves the economic program of the government and Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under this program, the IMF, the World Bank and the Japanese
government are to release funds which are "sufficient to refinance
the foreign debt payments falling due this year," Kasyanov said.
</P>
<P>
According to Kasyanov's predecessor, Mikhail Zadornov, Russia's
total foreign debts, aside from those inherited from the former
Soviet Union, now stand at 110 billion dollars, with over 17
billion falling due this year, about two-thirds of the country's
budget spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
