<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Measures to Uproot Drug Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Former Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani on Saturday called for practical measures to uproot
the production of narcotics in the world.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani made the appeal in a meeting with Deputy
U.N. Secretary General and Executive Director of the U.N. Drug
Control Program (UNDCP) Pino Arlacchi, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Instead of mere rhetoric, there should be efforts to present a
practical way of wide-scale global campaign against root causes
of narcotic drugs smuggling, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that the relevant international
organizations have not taken serious measure to uproot narcotics
production.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani pointed out that profitability of trade in drugs
has tempted dreadful mafia networks to infiltrate into media and
power control centers.
</P>
<P>
Such an influence has gone to an extent that the more Iran
steps up its campaign against "death merchants" (drug smugglers),
the more it comes under fire under the pretext of human rights
abuses, said Rafsanjani, chairman of Iran's powerful advisory
State Expediency Council.
</P>
<P>
He noted that as long as decisive and practical campaigns have
not been launched against drug production centers, the struggle
against the illicit phenomenon will not gain any success.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian President Mohammad Khatami in his separate
meeting with Arlacchi said that illicit drugs have posed a
serious threat to human societies.
</P>
<P>
Expressing pleasure with the effective cooperation between Iran
and the UNDCP in fighting drug trafficking, he said that
Iran has become a major barrier to trafficking of drugs to
the west.
</P>
<P>
Khatami also expressed Iran's interest in wide-scale
cooperation with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the scope of Iran's cooperation with the U.N. and
its subsidiary organizations should expand," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arlacchi, who are currently in Iran to attend a drug-burning
ceremony, said that the UNDCP intends to pave the grounds for
regional states to fight against narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Iran on Saturday afternoon burned 55 tons of narcotics to
mark the international anti-drug day.
</P>
<P>
He said that the international community appreciates Iran's
endeavors for the sake of the world health and stability and
now the wall of discrimination and misinformation against Iran
has broken.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. is willing to cooperate with Iran in carrying out
technical projects to secure success of the campaign against
illicit drugs, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
