<HEADLINE> Iranian FM Condemns Israeli Attacks on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi on Saturday expressed indignation over recent Israeli
attacks on Lebanon, which killed at least 8 people and incurred
damage on the country's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with his Lebanese counterpart Salim
Hoss, Kharrazi said that Iran is ready to extend aid to Lebanon to
repair the damages resulting from the Israeli attacks.
</P>
<P>
The signatories to the April 1996 agreement should take the
responsibility to exert pressure on Israel to terminate its
attacks on Lebanon, he stressed, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Hoss stressed the Lebanese people and government's
firm determination to counter the Israeli aggression and thanked
Iran for its support and assistance to his country.
</P>
<P>
Israel launched large-scale air strikes on Lebanon since
Thursday evening to avenge the Katyusha rocket attacks on its
northern areas by the Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was Israel's heaviest military offensive against Lebanon
since its "Grapes of Wrath" operation in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Under a ceasefire agreement signed in April 1996, the two
warring sides should refrain from attacks on or from civilian
targets.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi on Friday
also condemned the Israeli attacks on Lebanon and called on the
Muslim nations and the world community to urge Israel to abandon
criminal perpetration in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
