<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Set Afire 55 Tons Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Iran Saturday afternoon set aflame
55 tons of various narcotics seized from drug traffickers to mark
the international anti-drug day.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Deputy Secretary-General and Executive Director of the
U.N. International Drug Control Program Pino Arlacchi and senior
Iranian officials attended the ceremony on a hill in northern
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Due to hot whether, the drug pile caught fire itself and
started burning some 20 minutes before the ceremony began.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Fallah, secretary of the anti-drug headquarters at the
Iranian Presidential Office, said at the ceremony that Iran
seized some 54 tons of various drugs during the first three
months of the current Iranian year which started on March 21.
</P>
<P>
He said that in addition to some 30,000 Iranian security
personnel deployed along the country's 1,925-kilometer-long
eastern borders, Commander-in-Chief of the Iranian Armed Forces
Ali Khamenei last year ordered the Iranian army and the Islamic
Revolutionary Guards Corps to form military units in the region
to fight against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Fallah said that last year, 95 Iranian personnel were killed in
anti-drug actions while the number of the wounded and disabled was
four times of the figure.
</P>
<P>
He called on other countries and the world community to help Iran
combat drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
"There is no alternative but to conduct the anti-narcotics
campaign," he said.
</P>
<P>
In another ceremony on Friday, five tons of narcotics were
also set aflame in Iran's central province of Kerman to mark the
international anti-drug day.
</P>
<P>
The deputy secretary of the anti-drug headquarters, who was
only named as Heshmati, said at the ceremony that the country
allocates some 7,000 billion rials (about 2.3 billion
U.S. dollars) annually to fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
He said that some 270 Iranian personnel have been killed in
anti-drug campaigns since the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The official put the number of addicts in Iran at one million,
adding there are 210 million addicts throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Iran launched a large-scale anti-drug campaign after the Iranian
Majlis (parliament) passed a strict anti-drug law in 1989.
</P>
<P>
And the amount of confiscated narcotics have been on drastic rise
in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
