<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Warned Syria Before Air Raids on Lebanon: Arens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Prior to launching air raids on
Lebanon, Israel had warned Syria to stop Hezbollah guerrillas from
violating a 1996 cease-fire understanding which bars attacks
against and from civilian targets, Israeli Defense Minister Moshe
Arens said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Arens told Israel Radio that Israel had sent several messages
to Damascus in recent months, warning that it would not tolerate
Hezbollah attacks against Israel's northern areas.
</P>
<P>
"But unfortunately, the messages were not well received," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Hezbollah guerrillas fired Katyusha rocket salvos on
northern Israel on Thursday, killing two civilians.
</P>
<P>
Israel unleashed retaliatory air strikes against Hezbollah
bases and civilian targets in Lebanon on Thursday night, killing
at least eight people and destroying infrastructures such as power
stations and bridges.
</P>
<P>
This was the heaviest military offensive since Israel launched
the "Grapes of Wrath" operation against Lebanon in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed after the operation, the two warring
sides should refrain from attacks on or from civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military sources said Syria, the main power broker in
Lebanon, had seemingly begun to contain Hezbollah activities
after the air strike, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, is leading a war of attrition
to oust Israel from a 15-km deep border zone it carved out
in 1985 in south Lebanon with a declared aim of preventing
cross-border attacks against Israel's northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Israel said Damascus is using Hezbollah activities as leverage
to force Israel to withdraw from the Golan Heights it seized from
Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Though he accepts the United Nations Resolution 425 which
calls on Israel to withdraw from south Lebanon, the outgoing
Israeli government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu opposes
any territorial concession on the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, who defeated Netanyahu in the
May election, has pledged to pull Israeli troops out of Lebanon
within a year of office through negotiations with Syria, which
will necessitate territorial compromise on the Golan.
</P>
<P>
The talks with Syria have been frozen since they broke off in
early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Barak has distanced himself from the decision to strike
civilian targets in Lebanon. His office said he was informed only
after Netanyahu had made the decision.
</P>
<P>
But Arens said Barak did not oppose the strikes after learning
of the decision. Barak's office did not comment on Arens' remarks.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Palestinian National Authority
Saturday accused Israel of damaging Middle East peace efforts
by carrying out the air strikes against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"This dangerous escalation against Lebanon is a fatal strike
against the peace process and the international efforts to move
forward the Syrian and Lebanese negotiating tracks," the official
Palestinian news agency WAFA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
