<HEADLINE> Tanzanian PM Warns Youth of Drug Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye Saturday warned youths against drug abuse and
trafficking saying that the practice could destroy their precious
lives.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye gave the warning in the Tanzanian capital when
officiating a ceremony to mark the World Drug Day, saying it is a
shame for a nation like Tanzania to be used as a drug trafficking
center, adding that the influence of drugs is much more serious
than that of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
"We should not tolerate those who use our kids to enrich
themselves," he said, noting that any young people should engage
in income generating activities allowed by laws.
</P>
<P>
He said it is astonishing to see that people involving in the
business are those who were unable to buy return air tickets.
</P>
<P>
In the celebrations which were attended by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) resident representative Sally
Fegan-Wyles, Sumaye said concerted efforts are needed to fight
against the scourge.
</P>
<P>
Fegan-Wyles read a message of U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
that between three and four percent of the world's population
still regularly consume illegal substance.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister hailed non-governmental organizations (NGOs)
dealing with drug addicts for their commitment to help the youth.
</P>
</TEXT>
