<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of Labor
and Social Affairs Hassen Abdella Saturday called on parents and
educational institutions to play a leading role in protecting the
youth from the adverse effects of drug abuse and illicit drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by the minister at a meeting here to mark
this year's international day against drug abuse and illicit drug
trafficking which falls on June 26.
</P>
<P>
Hassen said saving the youth from the ill-effects of drug abuse
is not a task to be brushed aside to the government alone.
</P>
<P>
He urged the society in general and parents as well as schools
in particular to work together to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Ethiopian government has issued a
national anti- drug policy, adding that the government is fully
committed to implement continental and international conventions
against illegal drug activities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Vice-Minister of Health Lamisso Hayiso
said there is a rapidly growing tendency of cannabis cultivation
and consumption in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
He said as it is the case in other parts of the world, the most
 vulnerable group to drug abuse in Ethiopia is the youth.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of health has introduced a regular drug abuse
prevention educational program at 27 high schools in Addis Ababa
and Nazareth, he added. 
</P>
