<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Talks Seen to Break Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The British minister responsible
for Northern Ireland on Saturday expressed confidence that
last-minute talks to unblock the Northern Ireland peace process
would produce a deal next week.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a deal. I can't believe that anybody would not
realize the seriousness of the present situation. We'll make
something," Mo Mowlam was quoted telling BBC Ulster radio.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart
Bertie Ahern met leaders from across the province's political and
sectarian divide on Friday for four hours of talks aimed at
reviving the Good Friday peace deal signed last year.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders said progress was made but difficulties
remained over two issues -- when and how Irish Republican Army
(IRA) guerrillas would hand over their weapons, and the place of
the IRA's political wing Sinn Fein in a power-sharing executive.
</P>
<P>
Blair has set Wednesday as a deadline for finding a solution,
warning both sides that the province is "staring into the abyss".
He and Ahern will return to Belfast to chair the talks on Monday.
</P>
<P>
They say all parties linked to the Good Friday agreement on
Friday backed fundamental principles including guerrilla
disarmament by May 2000 and the creation of a power-sharing
provincial cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"I think the chances are better now than they were on Friday
because I think on Friday, when we agreed the principles that
everybody signed up to, that was an important groundbreaking first
step," Reuters quoted Mowlam as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the powerful Ulster Unionist Party said it was still
waiting for a commitment to IRA disarmament from Sinn Fein and
that it would have to see weapons being given up before allowing
the IRA's political wing into the new executive.
</P>
<P>
Next week's political wrangling will coincide with the tense
run-up to the annual Protestant Orange Order march through the
village of Drumcree, which has become a byword for sectarian
violence after bitter clashes between Catholic nationalists and
Protestant in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam appealed for calm ahead of the July 4 march, noting that
"both sides in Drumcree should step back and look at what people
in Northern Ireland are feeling."
</P>
<P>
The annual "marching season" in the province is a traditional
flashpoint as Protestants in bowler hats and sashes take to the
streets to celebrate centuries-old Protestant victories in battle.
</P>
</TEXT>
