<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French President to Attend EU-South America Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac left
here on Sunday for Brazil to attend the first summit of European
Union (EU) and South American countries to be held in Rio de
Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of his departure for Brasilia, Chirac said that he
hopes the summit can promote the political, economic and cultural
relations between the EU and South American countries.
</P>
<P>
He called on South American countries to build closer economic
and trade ties with Europe to avoid a domination by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU is worried about the U.S. strategy to
absorb the whole South American market into the North American
Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), which groups the United States,
Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to counter-balance the U.S. offensive, the EU
seeks to build a bilateral free trade zone with Argentina, Brazil,
Chile and Uruguay in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Brazilian newspaper "O Estrado de Sao
Paulo" published on Sunday, Chirac warned that a greater
integration of South American economies with the United States
will harm the EU's economic interests.
</P>
<P>
"France attaches great importance to the existence of a
balanced relationship between Latin America, the United States and
Europe. It wants a multi-polar world with strong economic entities
in different regions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state or government of 48 EU, South American and
Caribbean countries are expected to attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
The South American leaders have called on the EU to give up
trade protectionism as a condition for their closer economic and
trade relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
