<HEADLINE> Economists Call for Closer Links Among Mainland, HK, Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Economists from China's mainland,
Hong Kong and Macao agreed at a seminar held here on Sunday that
closer economic links should be promoted among them.
</P>
<P>
They said the three areas have become more interdependent
economically over the past two decades since the reform and
opening-up was launched in the mainland, and their cooperation is
also becoming stronger.
</P>
<P>
With Hong Kong's return and Macao's upcoming return to the
motherland, the three areas should seize the opportunities and
achieve common prosperity by making good use of their respective
advantages, according to the economists.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong should retain its status as a regional center of
finance, commerce, information and transportation, and such a
status is of great significance to the development of the mainland
and Macao, they said.
</P>
<P>
For the mainland and Hong Kong, there exist great potentials
for their cooperation in high-tech research and application. The
mainland enjoys strong scientific and technological facilities,
but many research achievements are put on the shelf. In comparison,
Hong Kong has developed market network and abundant
financial resources.
</P>
<P>
Macao has close links with the European Union, Taiwan and the
Pearl River Delta in south China. In this sense, Macao is able to
introduce advanced high technology to the Pear River Delta and
other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
And the products from the Peal River Delta and other areas of
China can be sold around the world with the help of established
marketing network in Macao and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
As for the close bonds between Hong Kong and Macao, Hong Kong
business people have been major investors in Macao's tourism,
gambling, manufacturing, export, real estate, finance,
telecommunications and transportation sectors.
</P>
<P>
With both areas practicing free market economy and enjoying a
high degree of autonomy, it is possible for the two to achieve
economic integration sometime in the future, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Speaks About Securities Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao
today called for a greater effort to safeguard the development of
the securities market as it is an integral part of the country's
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The securities market has played an active role in accelerating
China's economic development in the past few years and should be
used to support the reforms and development of state-owned
enterprises, Wen told a national meeting on the supervision and
regulation of futures and securities markets.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, which ended here today, was hosted by
the China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC), the nation's
securities watchdog, shortly before the country's first Securities
Law takes effect as of July 1.
</P>
<P>
By listing them on the stock market, the state-owned businesses
could raise capital, transform their management, and then
restructure totally, he said. Maintaining the healthy development
of the securities market will be of great importance.
</P>
<P>
Wen said that it will help by improving the supervision and
standardization of trading practices in the securities market, and
tough measures are needed to control the stock exchanges, listed
companies, securities companies, and intermediary institutions
according to law.
</P>
<P>
He said that the interests of investors need to be protected to
keep the securities market running safely and efficiently and the
qualifications of officials in charge of this need to be improved
in order to reduce market risks.
</P>
<P>
According to officials at the conference, the CSRC's branches
nationwide will start operation on July 1, forming a centralized
and unified network of securities supervisors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
