<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Opens Voltaire's Chateau to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The French government on Sunday
opened to the public a part of Chateau Ferney-Valtaire, a famous
residence castle of 18th century French philosopher Voltaire which
is located at the French-Swiss border, said organizers.
</P>
<P>
Visitors can visit the chamber of Voltaire with collections of
furniture, statues and paintings, including a portrait of Voltaire
by French painter Quentin de la Tour.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the castle, including a garden, a chapel, an
ancient church and an orangery, will remain closed to the public
until reparation work is completed.
</P>
<P>
Voltaire lived in the castle from 1759 to 1778 when he died.
He received there the elite of European intellectuals, conducted
dramas and wrote his philosophical tales.
</P>
<P>
The French government bought the castle from a private owner
in February this year and has put it on the list of 114 national
historical monuments and sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
