<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Official Expects Higher Oil Prices by Yearend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A Kuwaiti oil official
predicted on Sunday the oil prices might edge up beyond 18
U.S. dollars per barrel in the fourth quarter of 1999 due to the
cutdown of supplies in the world market.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he
based his estimation on many factors, mainly the reduction of oil
supply as a result of output cut by major oil producing countries,
the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the prospect of the world demand for oil to reach 1
million barrels per day (bpd) in the year would also help
lift the oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the growing demand to the "happy
ending of the economic crisis that stormed Asian countries in the
past couple of years, coupled with a boom in the U.S. and European
economies."
</P>
<P>
Another factor likely to prompt up the oil prices, he said, is
that non-Opec nations would not increase production this year due
to the sagging oil prices in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti oil official also voiced satisfaction over
the Opec member states' commitment to a production reduction
agreement that will expire in March 2000, saying the commitment
has yielded positive outcome, especially in the second quarter,
during which demand is traditionally weak..
</P>
<P>
Opec members, along with some non-Opec countries, agreed last
March to slash their output by about 2.1 million bpd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Should Be Improved Through Science: Jiang (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
today urged the armed forces of the country to increase their
consciousness of improving themselves through science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
He told delegates at the 14th Meeting of the People's
Liberation Army (PLA)'s Institutes of Higher Learning that the
armed forces should develop a large contingent of skilled
technological personnel who are loyal to the Communist Party of
China (CPC) and the people.
</P>
<P>
Since the Third Plenary Session of the CPC's 11th National
Congress in 1978, the PLA's institutes of higher learning have
trained a great number of people for military development and made
significant contributions to building a revolutionary, modern army,
said Jiang, who is also general secretary of the CPC Central
Committee and chairman of Central Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
He said that the institutes of higher learning have carried out
important instructions of Deng Xiaoping and that under the
military strategy in the new period, they have adapted to the
changing situation, continued reforms, and improved the quality
and standards of teaching.
</P>
<P>
The world is experiencing rapid changes in science and
technology while the military is undergoing profound changes, he
said. Information will be the greatest factor in fighting ability
in the battlefields of the future and this contest will be one of
high caliber personnel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Should Be Improved Through Science, Jiang (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang said that, in the face of new military developments in
the world, an effort needs to be made to strengthen defense and
the military's ability to cope with hi-tech regional wars.
</P>
<P>
The PLA's institutes of higher learning are training bases for
skilled personnel and they should receive top priority, Jiang said,
asking their leaders to work harder and accomplish more in their
courses.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that priority should be given to ideological and
political development. Efforts should be made to arm the students
with Marxism, Leninism, Mao Zedong Thought, and Deng Xiaoping
Theory so as to help them develop a correct view of the world, of
life, and of values and to enhance their sense of mission and
responsibility and of devoting themselves to national defense and
military development.
</P>
<P>
The institutes need to make sure that the students are
politically qualified, the president stressed, adding that the
level of students in the institutes has to be improved
comprehensively.
</P>
<P>
He said that the level and standards of the staff determine the
level of teaching and without a highly qualified contingent of
staff, talk about developing talented students will be empty talk.
</P>
<P>
A major reason why the Harbin Military Institute of Technology
became as prestigious as Beijing University and Qinghua University,
he said, is that it had a group of internationally famous
specialists and professors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
