<HEADLINE> France Calls on Israel, Hezbollah to End Reprisals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- France has called on Israel and the
Lebanese Shiite Muslim Hezbollah guerrillas to stop attacking each
other and "go out of the logic of reprisal."
</P>
<P>
The French envoy to the Middle East, Yves Aubin de la
Messuziere, who had discussed with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
and Prime Minister Salim Hoss, said in Beirut on Sunday that the
Committee of Surveillance of the Ceasefire in Lebanon is the only
right place to resolve violations against the 1996 ceasefire
agreement between Israel and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Surveillance, which consists of France, the
United States, Israel, Lebanon and Syria, will meet on Tuesday to
discuss the tension between Israel and Lebanon following the
Israel air raids against Lebanon last week.
</P>
<P>
Eight people were killed and about 60 injured in Lebanon during
the Israeli raids, which destroyed infrastructures of civil
service like bridges and electricity power plants and deprived
Beirut of electricity for three days.
</P>
<P>
Israel made the raids after two people were killed in rocket
attacks by Hezbollah on Galilee, a northern Israeli city.
</P>
<P>
Messuziere arrived in Beirut Sunday morning from Damascus,
where he met with Syrian President Hafez Assad, said French
Foreign Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
He was sent by French President Jacques Chirac to Lebanon to
show France's support to the country. Chirac has expressed his
regret about the Israeli air raids and said that France stands by
Lebanon in its new confrontation with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
