<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Marketing Future (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.'s NAPA, the automobile
parts company, opened its first distribution center in China here
today on a franchise basis.
</P>
<P>
The NAPA Lamba Auto Parts Chain Store Co. Ltd is one of
thousands of foreign or domestic franchises in China and analysts
predict that franchises will be China's favorite marketing form in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
The franchisee buys the rights to a franchiser's name and
established operating systems. Statistics show about a third of
the U.S.'s retail sales coming from franchise stores each year,
and every 7 minutes, a new one is opened.
</P>
<P>
China's franchise business was born out of the chain store
business and in its several years it has grown well, according to
Pei Liang of the China Chain Store &AMP; Franchise Association. He
says that 31 percent of the enterprises with annual sales above 50
million yuan last year were franchise stores.
</P>
<P>
China had some 90 chain stores in 1997, a third of which were
franchises. But last year, the number of chain stores with sales
above 50 million yuan hit 121, and 40 percent of those were
franchises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Ends Chronic Grain Shortage (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government and farmers
are now able to offer a definite answer to the question "Who will
feed China?" that aroused worldwide concerned four years ago as
continuous harvests have provided enough grain to the world's most
populous nation.
</P>
<P>
"China has put an end to the situation of chronic grain
shortages, and basically balanced its grain supply and demand, due
to good grain harvests in the past four consecutive years," said
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji at a recent grain marketing system
reform conference.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time China has confirmed a grain surplus for
a population of some 1.25 billion at a time when its grain
marketing reform is proceeding smoothly. The country experienced
regional grain oversupplies in 1984 and 1990, but officials at the
Ministry of Agriculture attributed this to a poor grain marketing
system.
</P>
<P>
Sector insiders estimate that China has increased its grain
output by more than 180 billion kg during the past four years,
while its grain demand only amounted to 50 billion kg in the same
period, with an obvious supply surplus over consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
"We were kept too busy growing grain in the past, but now we
can take our time. And moreover, we have sufficient grain reserves.
What do we need to worry about?" said Cui Shi'an, director of the
planting administration department of the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
China's agroscience level and calamity-resistance capacity have
grown to ensure grain harvests, with an output gap of only 10
billion kg, whether the years are good ones or lean ones, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
"China has no problem in maintaining and increasing grain
production, so long as it enjoys social and political stability,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Improved agricultural infrastructure and adoption of modern
agrosciences have made it possible for the country to stabilize
its annual grain production at about 500 billion kg, or some 400
kg for every Chinese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Ends Chronic Grain Shortage (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the past 50 years, China has managed to increase annual
grain output from 100 billion kilograms to 500 billion kilograms.
Insiders attribute the growth mainly to government policies and
investment in agricultural science and technology.
</P>
<P>
China's leaders have always placed agriculture at the top of
the national economic development agenda and have racked their
brains to find ways to provide food for all the people.
</P>
<P>
The household responsibility contract system, which was adopted
in the early 1980s, made farmers more enthusiastic about growing
grain and the two grain purchase price increases in the 1990s also
helped. Modern agronomy and the plastic sheeting and better
quality seed technology have begun to contribute to the country's
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Sufficient grain supplies have made it possible for the central
government and farmers to turn to higher quality grain types and
the government says that it will no longer protect poor-quality
crops.
</P>
<P>
"This move will affect farmers' incomes somewhat, but in the
long run, it will benefit them because China has no other choice
but to develop high-quality agriculture to feed its growing
population," according to Chen Ke, who is in charge of grain macro-
controls at the State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that China will have 1.3 billion people by the
year 2000 and 1.6 billion by 2030, so it will find itself in a
relatively tight situation, which is why the central government
wants badly to protect farmland, develop water-saving agriculture,
and tap the potential of agronomy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the grain marketing system reforms are intended to
raise farmers' and grain marketers' awareness of market
competition and to promote grain production and marketing while
giving a role to the world market in regulating China's grain
supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
The central government has always been sober-minded about food
problems as can be seen in the Agriculture Action Plan of China's
Agenda 21, where 10 out of 39 projects involve grain production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
