<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Leader Criticizes Dalai Lama's Separatism (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Legqog, the chairman of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, in an exclusive interview with Xinhua today
said that the Dalai Lama's separatism under the guise of
negotiations will never work and will be in vain.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama long advocated "Tibetan independence" and has
said repeatedly in recent years that he wants to negotiate with
China's central government, Legqog said, But his true intention is
to engage in divisiveness in the name of negotiations and this is
political trickery.
</P>
<P>
Since he fled abroad in 1959, the Dalai Lama has been obstinate
in his attempts to gain "Tibetan independence." In September of
1987 and June of 1988, he proposed a "Five-Point Plan" before the
Human Rights Sub-committee of the U.S. House of Representatives
and "New Proposals" at a press conference at the European
Parliament in Strasbourg, France.
</P>
<P>
On both occasions, he claimed to be holding negotiations with
the central government based on the "Five-Point Plan" and the "New
Proposals" but, Legqog said, the "Five-Point Plan" and "New
Proposal" in fact advocated "Tibetan independence" and the idea
that "Tibet was an independent country."
</P>
<P>
The essence of the Dalai Lama's position was the denial of the
fact that the Chinese government has full sovereignty over Tibet.
When the 10th Panchen Lama passed away in early 1989, the Buddhist
Association of China invited the Dalai Lama to return to China to
attend funeral services and its President Zhao Puchu handed over
an invitation letter to the Dalai Lama's representative but he
refused the invitation.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, there have been some riots in Lhasa that were
instigated by a small group of separatists. It has been shown that
the Dalai Lama's "government in exile" not only provided financial
aid to the separatists but also sent people to organize and
participate in the riots. They continue to hold so-called "
uprising commemorations" outside China on March 10 every year and,
on such occasions, the Dalai Lama himself will deliver speeches
and advocate divisiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Leader Criticizes Dalai Lama's Separatism (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legqog said that seeing China's international status improving
with its economic growth and social stability, the Dalai Lama had
to ask for renewed contacts with the central government and there
were proper channels for contacts and talks between his private
representative and Chinese central government departments, but the
representative made public information about the contacts and
distorted the contents in an attempt to mislead the public.
</P>
<P>
Several years ago, the Dalai Lama broke off all contacts with
the central government and shut the door on contacts. In recent
years, he has continued to move from one place to another,
reviving his claim that he wants to hold negotiations with the
central government, but he has continued to lie about the history
of Tibet at various public occasions and has attempted to mold
public opinion to support "Tibetan independence."
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama and his followers have never stopped their
propaganda and support for dividing the motherland in the Tibet
Autonomous Region and have been responsible for stirring up acts
of violence and terrorism in Lhasa and other places and have
plotted "peace marches" and "referendums" abroad.
</P>
<P>
They attempted to internationalize the "Tibet issue," Legqog
said. In March 1997, the Dalai Lama went to Taiwan where he
collaborated with "Taiwan Independence" forces and planned to open
an office of his "exiled government" in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The central government has stated repeatedly that it can
negotiate with the Dalai Lama and has welcomed him to end his
exile and return to the motherland to do things that benefit the
Tibetan people, provided that he completely abandons his notion of
"Tibetan independence" and recognizes that Tibet is an inseparable
part of China's territory and ceases his activities to divide the
motherland, Legqog said.
</P>
<P>
The central government's principled stand and basic attitude
have always been consistent and explicit, and the Dalai Lama knows
this. He is insincere in his desire to negotiate with the Chinese
central government and his claim that he wants to negotiate with
it is a mere pretext to deceive the world's people.
</P>
<P>
His attempt was to divide the motherland and to restore the
theocratic feudal system of serfdom that dominated Tibet with a
combination of political and religious power, Legqog concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
