<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Bombs Eritrea's Assab Airport Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian air force again
bombed Eritrea's Assab airport, a strategic military target, at
7:00 a.m. Sunday morning, Ethiopia announced here Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"This is the second attack on this strategic military target in
two days, " said a press statement issued here by the Office of
the Ethiopian Government Spokesperson Selome Taddesse.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian air force also attacked the airport at the Red
Sea port of Assab at 10:00 a.m. earlier on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The statement claimed that Sunday's "attack by the Ethiopian
air force caused extensive damage to the runway and Assab
airport."
</P>
<P>
But it did not mention the ground fighting between the
Ethiopian and Eritrean armies at the western front near the
vicinity of Mereb River which broke out Friday.
</P>
<P>
An earlier announcement made by the office Saturday evening
claimed that "5,950 Eritrean soldiers have been killed, captured
or wounded" in the fighting Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But so far Eritrea has not confirmed its toll.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea blamed each other for initiating more
fighting in the wake of renewed calls from the Organization of
Africa Unity (OAU) and the U.N. Security Council for immediate and
unconditional cease-fire between the two Horn of Africa neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Friday's offensive came after a one-week lull in hostilities.
Prior to that, there had been intense fighting around the Mereb
River from June 9 to 17.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian defense forces claimed to have put over 24,450
Eritrean soldiers out of action during the period, whereas Asmara
said its forces had killed or wounded more than 18,000 Ethiopian
soldiers during the week-long fighting.
</P>
<P>
The war between the two countries broke out on May 6,1998 over
a disputed stretch of their border area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
