<HEADLINE> Iran Suspends Planned Flight to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran's national flag carrier
Sunday canceled its planned first flight to Lebanese capital
Beirut because of the Israeli air blitz on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"The flight is due for today, but Iran Air cancelled it and
did not set the new date for it," said an official of Lebanon's
national airline Middle East Airline (MEA).
</P>
<P>
He said Iran Air made the decision in the wake of the Israeli
air strikes on Lebanon two days ago.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Iran Air and MEA signed an agreement to resume
flights between the two countries, which have been suspended since
the Iran 1979 Islamic revolution. MEA has made the first flight to
Tehran on May 21.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, Israel launched the biggest strike on
Lebanon since the 1996 "Grapes of Wrath" operation, killing at
least eight people and injuring more than 60 others.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed its attacks, which also destroyed the country's
power stations, road networks and a communication center, were
in retaliation for the cross-border attacks by the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah argued that it fired Katyusha rockets into northern
Israel in order to avenge the wounding of a Lebanese women by
Israeli shelling.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Hezbollah has been spearheading a guerrilla war
against the Israeli occupation troops out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
