<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents in Northern Israel Strike Over Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Israelis in the
north blocked major road junctions on Sunday as part of their
strike over the security and economic situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
A group of representatives of the demonstrators, including some
local council members, gathered in front of the Prime Minister
Office in Jerusalem to protest against the government's policy of
not paying economic compensation to the damage caused by the
Katyusha rocket attacks recently.
</P>
<P>
"The recent Katyusha attack on the north by Hezbollah has not
only caused security problems for us, but caused tremendous
economic demage to our economy and the government should
compensate that for us as it promised to do so," one protesters
told Xinhua in front of the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
"We just want to tell the outgoing government and the incoming
new government under Ehud Barak to settle the security issue in
the north and pay attention to our economic situation there
because daily business in the north has badly affected by the
attacks," the protesters added.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of Katyusha rocket attacks by the Lebanese
Hezbollah on the Galilee area in northern Israel occurred
Thursday, in which two people in Kiryat Shimona were killed and
nearly 30 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the rocket attacks, Israeli Air Force fighters
launched air strikes against Lebanese power and transformer
stations, key bridges and communication centers as well as
Hezbollah targets.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the northerners were once again ordered to
stay inside the bomb shelters due to the threat of shellings or
rockets from Lebanon. They were only allowed to return home Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During Sunday's demonstration, 13 local and regional councils
along the northern border also closed their municipal services to
the public, according to protesters.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the damage from Thursday's rocket attacks was
estimated at 5 million U.S. dollars, but the indirect effect on
local industry, tourism and business generally is expected to
reach millions more, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
