<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Discover Ancient Tombs in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists recently
unearthed 123 ancient tombs dating as far back as the Warring
States Period (475-221 B.C.) and as recent as the Qing Dynasty (
1644-1911) in Liulin County, north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary reports indicate that 78 tombs date to the Warring
States Period, 36 to the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 220 A.D.) and nine
to the Ming and Qing dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Chambers in the Warring States tombs are 3-5 meters long and 1.
8-4 meters wide. The tombs were found at a depth of 4-7 meters.
</P>
<P>
Most of the brick Han Dynasty tombs have been looted and
heavily damaged, with only one tomb containing recoverable relics
such as carved doors and pillars.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists note that 400-odd pottery, stone, bone, jade,
bronze, lacquer and porcelain recovered during the excavations
will be highly valuable for future research into the politics,
economy and culture in ancient China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
