<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Envoy Visits Lebanon on Israeli Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A French Senior Official Sunday
made a visit to Beirut to discuss the latest development after the
Israeli air blitz on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Yves Messuziere, who heads French Foreign Ministry's Middle
East and North Africa Department, held talks with Lebanese
President Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, he told a news conference that he discussed
the dangerous security situation on the borer with Lebanese
leaders and the solution to it.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that Lebanon and Israel end the
strike-and-revenge formula soon and settle the problem through
the international monitoring committee.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Hoss insisted that Lebanese government will
continue to support the resistance movement as long as any inch of
Lebanese land is occupied in the hands of Israel, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister hoped that the coming truce monitoring
committee approve a bill condemning the Israeli aggression on
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Thursday night, Israel launched the biggest strike on Lebanon
since the 1996 "Grapes of Wrath" operation, killing at least
eight people and wounding more than 60 others.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed its attacks, which also destroyed the
country's power stations, road networks and a communication
center, were in retaliation for the cross-border attacks by
guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah argued that it fired Katyushas into northern Israel
in order to avenge the wounding of a Lebanese women by Israeli
shelling.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah and Israeli forces have been in fighting nearly on a
daily basis.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring committee, compromising representatives from the
United States, France, Syria, Israel and Lebanon, was established
to oversee the implementation of a cease-fire understanding
reached between Hezbollah and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The committee is scheduled to convene under Lebanon's request
to review the complaints filed by both Lebanon and Israel who
charge each other for violating the understanding.
</P>
<P>
Messuziere came here Sunday morning from Damascus, where he
held talks with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad on the same
issue.
</P>
<P>
With 35,000 troops stationed in Lebanon, Syria is the main
power broker in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
