<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11th Panchen Lama Attends Thangka Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIGAZE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The 11th Panchen Lama attended a
summer thangka-exhibition ceremony at Tibet's Zhaxi Lhunbo
Lamasery today and presented hada (white silk used as a gift) for
the lamasery's thangkas (paintings on brocade) featuring prominent
Buddhas.
</P>
<P>
Today is May 14 on the traditional Tibetan calendar and for
more than 500 years, for three days starting today, three thangkas
with the Amitaya, Sakyamuni, and Maiyuiri Buddhas are placed in
the sun up against a 40-meter wall to bring good luck and dispel
disasters.
</P>
<P>
Lamas and many Buddhists who traveled long distances to the
lamasery prostrated themselves and presented hadas and prayed that
Buddha may help dispel disasters and bring good luck.
</P>
<P>
The 11th Panchen Lama went up onto a roof of a hall and waved
to the crowd of worshipers who paid their respects to the 9-year-
old lama.
</P>
<P>
Erdeni Losang Qamba Lhunzhub Qoigyijabu, the 11th Panchen Lama,
returned to Zhaxi Lhunbo Lamasery on June 20 after religious
activities in Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region,
southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Zhaxi Lhunbo covers 300,000 sq.m. and has been the residence of
all previous Panchen Lamas. It was built in 1447 and is one of six
major monasteries of Tibetan Buddhism and a major place for
Tibetan Buddhists to perform religious activities.
</P>
<P>
The lamasery houses the world's largest bronze image of Buddha
that is 26.7 meters tall. The hands of the statue are 3.2 m long
and the shoulders are 11.5 m wide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
