<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Says UNSCOM Spying Charges Understandable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
has confirmed that there was some evidence showing that U.N.
weapons inspectors in Iraq were involved in spying for the United
States.
</P>
<P>
"I think there was a measure of justification in those
allegations and Washington never denied it," Annan told BBC
television on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Scott Ritter, a former weapon inspector, had
said Washington used the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), which
was in charge of Iraqi disarmament, to obtain information on how
to topple Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the allegation was understandable.
</P>
<P>
"The suspicion will always be there: 'Are they coming to disarm
or are they coming to spy'," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"That was worrisome because it not only undermined UNSCOM but
it could undermine future disarmament regimes," he said.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has not been in Iraq since U.S.-British bombing raids in
last December.  
</P>
</TEXT>
