<HEADLINE> 35,460 Road Accidents in Lagos State Over Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Road Safety Commission
said a total of 35,460 road accidents were recorded in Nigeria's
Lagos State between 1989 and 1999, averaging 10 accidents daily.
</P>
<P>
In the accidents, 7,264 people were killed with about 5,384
being males and 1,880 females during the period, The Post Express
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Lagos State Sector Commander Kayode Olagunju
as saying recently that 19,446 males and 14,021 females were
injured respectively during the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that a total of 50,426 vehicles were involved in
the accidents, adding that 22,673 of the vehicles involved were
privately owned with 3,603 identified as taxis.
</P>
<P>
Some 13,447 offenders were booked for 27,754 offenses while
3,071 vehicles were impounded between January 1989 and June 22,
1999, according to the commander.
</P>
<P>
He noted that illegal bus stops, wrong lane parking, location
of bus stops at junctions and deplorable road conditions are some
of the major causes of the chaotic traffic situation in the state.
</P>
<P>
Based on these statistics, the commission has deployed five
vehicles and five motor cycles to intensify patrols within the
metropolises, the commander added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
