<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Western Leaders to Help Repair Damaged Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
on Sunday urged the western leaders to help repair damaged
Yugoslavia before there is another humanitarian disaster in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"We have to make sure that the Serbs, who in some ways are
victims, should not be twice punished," Annan told the BBC's
Breakfast with Frost program.
</P>
<P>
"We said at the beginning of the war that the fight was not
with the Yugoslav people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we say we are only going to offer humanitarian assistance,
I hope we are going to define it in a broad manner to include
electrical supplies and water, which are life sustaining," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said electricity and water systems in Yugoslavia had been
destroyed by 10 weeks of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief warned of another refugee crisis if power was not
restored by the onset of the harsh Balkan winter.
</P>
<P>
"Come winter, if (the Serb people) have no heat, they may also
be on the move," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Each time I have the chance I am telling the NATO leaders
that we need to be careful not to box ourselves in. If we do that,
it will create another humanitarian disaster," said the secretary
general.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the rebuilding of the whole southeastern European
region would take about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
He said aid should be offered irrespective of whether President
Slobodan Milosevic stays in power.
</P>
<P>
NATO countries like the United States and Britain had ruled out
any money to rebuild Yugoslavia without a change of government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile in Kosovo, tensions between Serbs and ethnic
Albanians remain high, as Albanians continue to conduct reprisals.
</P>
<P>
Albanians in Kosovo have looted and torched thousands of Serb
houses across Kosovo since NATO arrived, a BBC report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Albanians are settling scores, and until
NATO stops the reprisals, it will not be able to restore law and
order or impose peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
