<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Energy Minister Concludes Visit to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Minister of Energy and
Mineral Resources Suleiman Abu-Aleem said here Sunday that Jordan
and Iraq agreed on developing oil relations and hoped that the U.N.
embargo imposed on Iraq would be lifted soon.
</P>
<P>
Abu-Aleem made the remarks in a statement before his departure.
</P>
<P>
He said he was happy of the results of his four-day visit to
Iraq. Joint minutes were signed by the two sides on Saturday
evening to tackle an agreement of last January that is part of a
bilateral oil protocol to secure Jordan's needs for crude oil.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rasheed said after signing
the joint minutes that "Iraq is ready to meet the needs of any
Arab country" for crude oil.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed praised the oil cooperation between Iraq and Jordan,
saying "it is a good example for the joint Arab cooperation," the
Iraqi News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Abu-Aleem, who left for home Sunday, said in Baghdad upon his
arrival on Wednesday that he would discuss with Iraqi officials on
the possibility for the Jordanian Petroleum Company to develop an
Iraqi oil field.
</P>
<P>
However, Saturday's joint minutes made no mention about that,
which indicates that the two sides have not reach an agreement on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
Under the joint Iraqi-Jordanian oil protocol signed last
January, Iraq will provide Jordan with 4.8 million tons of crude
oil in 1999 at preferential prices.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the 1991 Gulf War, Iraq has provided all
Jordan's needs for crude oil and derivatives under U.N. permission.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced earlier that Iraq and Jordan were preparing for
the final stages to start the construction of an Iraqi-Jordanian
oil pipeline which will be executed on stages, the joint minutes
did not mention that either. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
