<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Urged to Change for Curbing AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF)
has urged Kenyans to change their behaviors to curb the spread of
HIV/AIDS as the AIDS-related deaths had reached an "alarming"
proportion.
</P>
<P>
AIDS awareness should be translated into practical behavioral
changes if the trend is to be reserved, UNICEF country
representative Crispin Wilson said when closing a week-long AIDS
awareness workshop in Mombasa, Kenya's southeastern port city, at
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Wilson noted that the UNICEF had spent millions of shillings on
AIDS prevention since the first case was reported in Kenya in
1984.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Nation newspaper quoted him as saying that the
infant mortality rate had gone up to 72 percent from 60 percent in
the past few years due to the spread of the virus.
</P>
<P>
He was puzzled that in Kenya, although the AIDS awareness rate
was estimated at 90 percent, only five percent was translated into
action practically.
</P>
<P>
Wilson also noted his organization had decided to include
teachers in the AIDS awareness program as they were in touch with
the most vulnerable group which consisted of youths aged between
15 and 24 years.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by Kenya's National AIDS Control Program
which was tabled at the workshop indicates that the rapid increase
in young adult deaths would have serious impact on development.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative number of AIDS deaths would increase from the
current 100,000 to a million by the year 2000 and to over 2.1
million by the year 2005, the report says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
