<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Disciplines Would-be Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
has prepared a code of conduct for his in-coming cabinet, warning
the would-be ministers to be prepared for the coming sacrifice and
tough responsibilities, or be ready to go.
</P>
<P>
"Accepting to serve in this administration means complete
dedication to leadership, total commitment to hard work and
stringent discipline, there is no other way to make Nigeria great
again," he said in capital Abuja Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As means of involving the new helmsmen in the crusade,
President Obasanjo proposed the code of conduct that would be
presented later, which, according to him, will be more stringent
than before.
</P>
<P>
"Ministers should agree to the code of conduct as a proof that
they would lead by example," the New Nigerian newspaper Sunday
quoted the president as saying.
</P>
<P>
Accepting the job at this time meant full recognition of the
implication and responsibility of public office, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He further explained that the essence of the anti-corruption
bill, which has been presented to the national assembly, is to
have a law to back the crusade and to have an anti-corruption
commission that would be empowered to "seek, find and recover."
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, who described his three-week presidency as "very
rough", predicted a "rough" experience for the incoming ministers.
</P>
<P>
"You must be prepared to make sacrifice, if any sacrifice for
this purpose is considered too much, it would be better not to
accept the responsibility", he said.
</P>
<P>
During a retreat with the ministers, which the president put as
an occasion for the would-be ministers to ponder and deliberate
fundamental issues pertaining to their assignments, Obasanjo said
that Nigeria's experience of bad governance was characterized by
federal ministers who systematically abused the privilege of
public office.
</P>
<P>
The president briefed the would-be ministers on the current
anti- corruption campaign, urging them to disabuse their minds of
the "wrong notion that one ministry is more lucrative than
another."
</P>
<P>
"There would be no juicy ministries under our administration,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He told the nominees, who would be sworn in Wednesday, that the
 challenge of minimizing corruption is daunting, adding that there
was no other choice but to fully confront it with determination
and cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
