<HEADLINE> Washington Protesters Urge U.S., NATO to Rebuild Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (xinhua) -- About 100 protesters marched in
downtown Washington on Saturday to urge the U.S. and its NATO
allies to rebuild infrastructure in Yugoslavia destroyed during
their recent 79-day bombing.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, holding signs including "End NATO Occupation
of Yugoslavia," "Humanitarism is not a Victory," and "Bring Back
Troops Now," gathered at the Dupont Circle at about noon time.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the rally, several of them urged the U.S. and its
allies to meet their moral obligations by helping Yugoslavia to
rebuild the bridges, hospitals and schools destroyed during the U.
S.-led NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
"We call upon the U.S. and NATO to meet their moral obligation
and finance the reconstruction of the once-beautiful Yugoslavia,"
said Carol Moore, a war tax resister.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said earlier this week that "not a
penny" will be spent on helping rebuild the civilian
infrastructure in Yugoslavia so long as Yugoslav leader Slobodan
Milosevic remains in power.
</P>
<P>
This policy is "not only immoral, but also illegal," said
Malcom Cannon, Washington Director of the International Action
Center (IAC).
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators then marched to the headquarters of the
American Broadcasting Company (ABC) chanting slogans "Clinton we
say no, NATO out of Kosovo," and "NATO, NATO you can't hide,
bombing is genocide."
</P>
<P>
"ABC, shame on you!" the protesters chanted in front of the ABC
building. "ABC is too biased and one-sided in covering the war," a
woman protester told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"It's ok to kill Serbs, bomb the bridges, the hospitals, is it
the message ABC wants to send out to the world?" she asked.
</P>
<P>
They also marched a few blocks to the building of The
Washington Post, in front which, Moore destroyed "our invoices for
subscriptions" to the newspaper "because of its editorial support
for the brutal, immoral and illegal bombing of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
"The Washington Post is a pro-war newspaper. When 10,000
marched to the Pentagon two weeks ago, it took the Post a whole
week to mention the largest anti-war rally in nearly ten years,"
Moore said.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration is one of a series of protests organized by
the IAC, set up by Ramsey Clark, the former U.S. attorney-general.
</P>
<P>
IAC is outlining "a multi-point indictment of the U.S.
government's conduct in the war against Yugoslavia" through a
Commission of Inquiry initiated by Clark for the International War
Crimes Tribunal, Cannon told Xinhua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
