<HEADLINE> UAE Firms Hire Students as Hot Summer Comes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- As the hot summer comes and
many employees go on vacation, firms in the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) are turning to undergraduates to fill vacant posts, the
Gulf News daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of hands and the cost factor are driving companies
to think about taking on students, according to Yousef Tuqan,
support and services manager at Abra, a recruitment company which
has been advertizing for university students to apply for
temporary jobs and internships over the summer.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown during the summer makes high-paid replacements
unviable, he explained to the paper. So Abra made the move to
introduce the idea of student summer interns to companies and the
response has been very positive.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody wins," said Tuqan. "Many of the college students get
hands-on experience and make contacts in their fields," he added.
</P>
<P>
The young recruits have to meet the prescribed federal and
company requirements, such as being of legal working age, before
taking up jobs. The salaries paid to them is something to be
negotiated by the hiring company and the prospective summer temp.
</P>
<P>
Jobs available for university students on a temporary basis
throughout the summer include public relations posts, customer
service, sales, or just being an extra pair of hands around the
office, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
