<HEADLINE> Kenya Commercial Bank to Close 124 Branches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Commercial Bank has said it
will close down 124 branches across the country as the government
announced its plan to divest from it, the sunday Standard
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Peter Nyakiamo, Executive Chairman of the bank, told
share-holders at the bank's annual meeting here Saturday that the
closure would make the bank service more efficient and cost
effective.
</P>
<P>
He said a major branch rationalization program would be taken
soon with an aim of reducing its total outlets from the current
275 to 151.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Permanent Secretary Margaret Chemingich
confirmed that the government was in the process of divesting from
the bank.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government reduced its share-holding in the
commercial bank from 60 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the management board of the bank, of the bank's
9.6 billion shillings (about 140 million U.S. dollars)
non-performing loans, 1.4 billion shillings had been recovered in
a record time of three months.
</P>
<P>
Nyakiamo also announced significant restructuring steps in the
bank aimed at achieving improved debt collection and cost
containment.
</P>
<P>
The bank plans to reduce its staff from 4,500 to 3,000 in the
next two or three years to enchase cost saving and increase
revenue base, the executive chairman noted, saying that it would
dispose of surplus assets to earn the bank revenue and reduce
overhead costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
