<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Works to Ease Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
is making great efforts to ease air pollution, especially problems
caused by acid rain, smoke and dust and auto exhaust emissions.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, some 17 cities, covering 63 percent of the
province's total area, have become victims of acid rain which has
brought about an annual economic loss of four billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
With rapid urbanization, pollution caused by automobile exhaust
has become serious in the province. At the same time, sulfur
dioxide, smoke and dust are major air pollution problems in its
cities.
</P>
<P>
A local environmental protection official said that to solve
the problems, the provincial government will reduce pollution
resulting from the use of coal by adjusting its energy structure
and limiting the use of coal and oil with more than one percent of
sulphur content.
</P>
<P>
The province will not approve construction projects with coal-
burning power plants in urban areas or city suburbs, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, many industrial enterprises causing air
pollution, such as cement plants, will be closed by the end of
this century, he said.
</P>
<P>
The province will tackle exhaust emissions by stopping selling
leaded gasoline and tightening controls over motor vehicles, he
said, adding that automobiles failing to meet emission standards
will not be allowed to enter into the market, and they are
required to install emission control equipment before being sold.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Guangdong is to carry out the "Blue Sky" drive, a
ten-year environmental improvement project aimed at improving air
quality and controling acid rain, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The project will require a total investment of 5.4 billion yuan.
When it is completed, most of the industrial enterprises and
service businesses in the province will replace coal, their
current fuel, with natural gas, which is economical and
environmentally friendly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 07:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Moves Closer to Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak seems to move toward a narrow government after signing
a coalition agreement with the left-wing Meretz party, making it
the third coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which was signed late Saturday night,
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid will become education minister in the
new cabinet. The party will also get the trade and industry
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The deal came after Barak signed coalition agreements Friday
with Yisael ba'Aliya, the Russian immigrant party, and the
National Religious Party, which champions Jewish settlement in the
 West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Although winning a landslide in the May election for prime
minister, Barak has had to struggle to forge a coalition from
the 15 factions in the 120-seat parliament, each with demands
as diverse as Israeli society, since his Labor-led One Israel
alliance controls only 26 seats.
</P>
<P>
With the joining of the three partners, Barak's coalition
now has 47 seats, still short of the minimum number of 61
seats required to form a government.
</P>
<P>
He has courted the second and the third largest parties, the
right-wing Likud and the ultra-Orthodox party Shas, in order to
form a broad-based coalition as he promised after the elections.
</P>
<P>
But the inclusion of Meretz, which opposes to sit together
with Shas, indicated that Barak might be heading for a narrow
coalition of 66 seats, while leaving the door open for Shas
and Likud.
</P>
<P>
The talks with Shas, which seizes 17 seats in the parliament,
broke off Friday on disputes over the distribution of cabinet
portfolios. Shas was especially unhappy that Barak granted the
interior ministry, which has been under its control for 15 years,
to Yisrael ba'Aliya.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said Sunday that One Israel will continue talks
with Shas later in the day. The talks with Likud will resume only
after the negotiations with Shas end.
</P>
<P>
There has been strong opposition, both inside Likud and One
Israel, to the inclusion of Likud in the coalition. Some Likud
members said the right-wing party, which plunged to 19 seats from
32 seats in the elections, can only be rebuilt while sitting in
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Senior One Israel members, meanwhile, said bringing in the
Likud would not help Barak carry out his promise to move forward
the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
