<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Anticipates Bigger Role in Int'l Sports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region of China is determined to reinforce its
image as an international metropolis by playing a more active role
in the world sports arena.
</P>
<P>
This was reflected by Hong Kong's recent decision to bid for
the 2006 Asian Games for the first time in its history.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong athletes, in the name of "Hong Kong, China" in Asian
and international sports events, achieved remarkable success in
1998 by winning a total of 68 gold, 76 silver and 65 bronze
medals.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong delegation ranked 13th among the 43 participating
delegations with five golds, six silvers and six bronzes at the
13th Asian Games in Bangkok last December. It is the most
remarkable success it had ever scored.
</P>
<P>
This year Hong Kong has played host to such world class events
as the Fourth World Short Course Swimming Championship, the Tenth
Hong Kong Open - a stop of ATP Tour, and Diving Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
In early May, Hong Kong successfully hosted China's National
Archery Champions Championship -- the first national sports event
held in Hong Kong since its return to China two years ago.
</P>
<P>
This shows that Hong Kong opens the door to Chinese mainland's
sports events and will develop sports in close coordination with
the mainland.
</P>
<P>
As to Kong Kong's bid for the Asian Games, President of Hong
Kong's Sports Federation and Olympic Committee (SF&AMP;OC) Timothy Fok
said: "With the help of the HKSAR government, we do have
confidence in bidding for the Games and developing Hong Kong,
especially in the area of sports in depth."
</P>
<P>
Fok said he believes that hosting Asian Games would bring about
substantial benefits to Hong Kong's economy including major
contributions to enhancing tourism industry, stimulating the
region's sports, reinforcing its international city image and
providing more working opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Home Affairs David Lan said the SAR government
backs the SF&AMP;OC bidding for international events such as the Asian
Games, and playing host to these sports events will surely
rejuvenate Hong Kong, especially in the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, as a regional business and financial center,
possesses convenient communications, a great number of hotels and
advanced telecommunication. And the city is also on the way of
economic recovery from the setbacks caused by the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Fok pointed out that with the support from the government and
the people from all walks of life, Hong Kong's sports associations
had full confidence in bidding to host the 2006 Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
The SF&AMP;OC has been in existence since 1951. But in the past 48
years, Hong Kong had never hosted a major international games.
</P>
<P>
Now, the biggest obstacle for Hong Kong's bid for the Asian
games is the lack of a multi-functional sports complex,
especially a stadium that could run major games' opening and
closing ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
At present, the largest sports complex in Hong Kong is a
40,000-seat Hong Kong Stadium exclusively for football matches.
</P>
<P>
"To establish more sports facilities is our main goal,
particularly in schools, because efficient sports facilities could
offer more training opportunities for the young people," said Fok.
</P>
<P>
Apart from football, Hong Kong's sports are amateur nowadays.
To develop the city's sports and make it be accustomed to the
professionalism trend in the international sports arena, Hong Kong
SF&AMP;OC deleted the word "amateur" from its former title early this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
