<HEADLINE> UNDCP Allocates 13 Million Dollars for Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Executive Director of the U.N. Drug
Control Program (UNDCP) Pino Arlacchi announced here on Saturday
that the UNDCP has allocated 13 million U.S. dollars for Iran to
fight against narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Following the opening of the UNDCP office in Tehran, he said
that 7 million dollars of the sum is to go to controlling borders
and the remaining 6 million dollars to research works, addicts'
rehabilitation and raising awareness of local communities.
</P>
<P>
The allocation do not represent assistance to Iran, rather
it marks cooperation between Iran and the U.N. body to control
drugs, the Islamic Republic News Agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Arlacchi, who is also deputy U.N. secretary general,
did not mention the term for the allocation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Secretary of the anti-drug headquarters at the
Iranian Presidential Office Mohammad Fallah said that excluding
the sum spent by the security forces and the Islamic
Revolutionary Guards Corps and related organizations, his
headquarters spends as much as 120 million dollars annually on
drug control.
</P>
<P>
To mark the international anti-drug day, Iran burned 55
tons of narcotics on Saturday afternoon in northern Tehran to
show its determination to continue campaign against drug
trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
