<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 06:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renal Diseases on Rise in GCC States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Renal failure incidence has
registered a sharp increase in the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
member states, with patients in end stage alone numbering about
3,250 every year.
</P>
<P>
According to studies, the incidence of renal failure has rose
from 80 patients per million in 1980s to 130 patients per million
per year now, the Khaleej Times daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are over 6,000 nationals and expatriates on
dialysis therapy in GCC countries, which group Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
Faced with the alarming rise in renal failure cases, these
states have initiated efforts to create public awareness and find
religious and social support for medical procedures governing
organ transplants, in addition to expanding dialysis facilities,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Kidney transplant operations are being performed in Saudi
Arabia, Kuwait, Oman and the UAE, but the relative donors remain
few. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
