<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trees Dying for Unknown Disease in Northern Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of trees have been dying
at least in three districts in northwestern Bangladesh for an
"unknown disease," the latest issue of the news weekly Dhaka
Courier reported.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the death of such a large number of trees in the
districts of Pabna, Sirajganj and Rangpur is yet to be detected,
as some experts hold one kind of fungus responsible while others
suspect that the deficiency of some nutrients in the soil is
responsible.
</P>
<P>
There are no official figures as to how many trees have died so
far because of this "mysterious" disease, but unofficial estimates
say that at least 30 percent of the trees in the districts have
died over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
The report said a senior scientific officer of the Forest
Research Institute, Chittagong visited Pabna district, some 130
kilometers northwest of here, and three other adjacent districts,
and after an exhaustive survey concluded that the trees were dying
because of one kind of fungus attack.
</P>
<P>
He suggested spraying of some fungicide over the infected trees
but it did not work, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Professor Iqbal Zuberi, chairman of the Botany Department of
Rajshahi University, in northwestern Bangladesh, said a few years
ago that the death of the trees was the manifestation of a
desertification process in the northwestern region.
</P>
<P>
But a scientific officer of a local Government and Rural
Development project in Dinajpur, 286 kilometers northwest of the
capital city, said that deficiency of certain nutrients in the
soil of the northwestern districts was responsible for the death
of the trees. The micro-nutrients in the soil of the flood-prone
northwestern districts were lost to receding flood waters, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural experts working in these districts said that
intensive cultivation of high-yield variety of paddy dependent on
underground irrigation facilities had resulted in the depletion of
micro-nutrients like zinc and sulfur in the soil and underground
water, and these might have been the cause of the death of the
trees.
</P>
<P>
The death of trees has posed a serious threat to the
environment of the region, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
