<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Eyes Tamil Diaspora to End Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched a new
initiative that could represent an important change in its
approach to counter the long-standing rebellion by secessionist
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In an imaginative twist to the "hearts and minds" component of
counter-insurgency doctrine, it is for the first time trying to
reach out to the extensive Tamil diaspora.
</P>
<P>
"There are 600,000 to 800,000 people of Sri Lankan Tamil origin
overseas but we've traditionally had very little contact with
them," Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar told Jane's Defense
Weekly in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the Foreign Ministry started a monthly
newsletter in Tamil for the expatriate community.
</P>
<P>
The main aim is to explain that Sri Lanka has changed, and to
provide them with an alternative source of information about the
country.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that the initiative finally aims to
curtail LTTE's funding which has played a crucial role in
prolonging the civil war.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has established more than 40 overseas offices since
1983 when they launched its rebellion against the Sri Lankan
government for an independent Tamil homeland in the north and east
of the country.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that LTTE's overseas offices generate 4-6
million U.S. dollars monthly in support of its cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
