<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Say Philippines' Mayon Restive Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' most active
volcano, Mayon, is restive again with an increased emission of
sulfur dioxide after its eruption last Tuesday, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Standard newspaper Sunday quoted experts of the
Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (Phivolcs) as
saying that the institute placed Mayon's emission of sulfur
dioxide at 4,700 tons per day, well above the normal rate of 500
tons.
</P>
<P>
The experts said that if present indications continue, the
alert status will have to be raised from the existing level 1 to
2.
</P>
<P>
Alert level 2 means the six-kilometer permanent danger zone
around the volcano will be widened to seven kilometers.
</P>
<P>
According to the experts, the volcanic debris accumulated after
Mayon's eruption last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mayon's eruption last week lasted for about 10 minutes, raining
ash on surrounding areas in the eastern part of the Philippines.
But no casualties had been reported during the eruption.
</P>
<P>
Mayon, the most active volcano in the world, has erupted at
least 40 times since 1616. The volcano's eruption on February 2,
1993 killed 78 people and affected 17,119 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
