<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies LA-EU Summit Threatening Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States does not
see its interests threatened by the rapprochement to be built
during the Latin America-European Union summit, which will be held
June 28-29 in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The view was expressed by Arturo Valenzuela, new presidential
advisor for Latin American affairs, in an exclusive interview with
the Brazilian daily "Folha de Sao Paulo" on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Valenzuela denied that the LA-EU Summit, to be attended by
heads of state and government of 33 Latin American and Caribbean
countries and 15 European Union countries, might be seen by the
United States as a threat to its strong commercial influence in
the Latin American region.
</P>
<P>
He said, the LA-EU Summit could be an instrument for the
Americas to achieve the opening of the "restrictive" European
market, which could mean good news for world trade.
</P>
<P>
Valenzuela said that the summit will not set back the timetable
for implementing the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA) by the
year 2005 and that the real obstacle to for the creation of FTAA
is on the side of the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Clinton will not get the "fast track"
approval from the U.S. Congress until the end of his term even
though FTAA will continue to be a priority for his administration.
</P>
<P>
However, experts here believe that the United States is worried
by the eventual approach of the EU to Latin America and the
Caribbean and for the possible creation of a free trade area
between the EU and Mercosur in 2005.
</P>
<P>
They note that the United States does not like to see a rising
political, economic, and commercial influence of Europe or any
other part of the world in Latin America, because it traditionally
regards the region as its backyard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
