<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0300 GMT, June 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak arrived in
Washington on Saturday for a working visit. He is expected to meet
U.S. President Bill Clinton on Thursday, and supposed to leave
Washington to go back to Egypt later that evening. (US-Egypt-
Mubarak)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- More than 2,000 scientists and decision-makers from
all over the world are discussing the challenges and opportunities
of science in the next century as the World Conference on Science
opened here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
By bringing together representatives from all scientific fields,
the conference, entitled Science for the 21st century, will debate
the achievements, shortcomings and challenges of science as well
as its social, economic and ethnic implications in the decades to
come. (Hungary-Conference-Science)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Romania agreed Saturday to grant the passage
through its airspace to 10 Russian aircraft en route to Kosovo
transporting peacekeeping soldiers and military equipment.
</P>
<P>
Romania will treat Russia's request as an emergency case, which
means permission could take effect without approval from the
parliament, said the communique. Under Romanian laws, the passage
of foreign troops should be endorsed by the parliament except for
special and emergency cases, which can be permitted only by the
president. (Romania-Russia-Air Corridor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif will be
paying a working visit to China from June 28 to July 3 at the
invitation of his Chinese counterpart, announced the Pakistani
Foreign Office Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is scheduled to hold an in-depth exchange of views with
the Chinese leadership on a wide range of subjects including
political, economic, regional and international issues, according
to a Foreign Office press release.
</P>
<P>
Special focus will be placed on security, peace and economic
development in the region against the backdrop of the current
volatile situation in South Asia. (Pakistan-PM-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian peacekeepers will enter Kosovo group by
group in 40-45 days, and will stay there till June 10, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Leonid Ivashov, head of the Defense Ministry's International
Cooperation Department, said here Saturday that Russia sent its
first military transport aircraft to Kosovo earlier Saturday,
carrying airport service personnel and navigation equipment to the
Slatina Airport. (Russia-Kosovo-Deployment) 
</P>
</TEXT>
