<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Trade Set to Pick Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Bilateral trade and economic
cooperation between China and Japan will step into recovery, the
Business Weekly reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show the Sino-Japanese trade volume
declined by 4.8 percent to 57.9 billion U.S. dollars during the
1997-98 period and Japanese investment also slumped due to the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
As a result, pessimism has grown in the two countries'
economic circles.
</P>
<P>
However, Guo Li, an official in the Asian Affairs Department
of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, was
quoted by the weekly as saying: "There is no reason for woe. There
is still huge potential for further development since the
complementary advantages of the Chinese and Japanese economies
have not been fully brought out."
</P>
<P>
Guo interpreted the declines in bilateral trade and economic
cooperation mainly as an "adjustment." "This had been very obvious
even before the outbreak of the financial crisis," she added.
</P>
<P>
She called for efforts by the two countries to foster new
growth points in their bilateral economic cooperation, especially
in the Chinese exports to Japan.
</P>
<P>
She suggested China improve its export product mix and Japan
make more efforts in market access, technology transfer and direct
investment in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur Calls for Clear Rules of Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The South American Common
Market (Mercosur) will express its hope at the Latin America-
European Union summit that clear free trade rules will be worked
out to accommodate the interests of all parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
In a written interview with Xinhua, Argentina Foreign Deputy
Minister Andres Cisneros expressed the hope on the eve of the
summit which will be held here on June 28-29.
</P>
<P>
The summit is aimed at starting firm negotiations toward a free
trade agreement and deepening mutual understanding between the
European and Latin American economic blocs.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Mercosur is expected to make two fundamental
achievements at the summit: a firm commitment to free trade and
the formation of political consensus in the region, two pillars
for the bloc to negotiate with its European counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The starting line for Mercosur is to push the EU to gradually
eliminate its subsidies that damage Latin America's production and
export capabilities and cause great imbalances in bilateral trade,
said Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
Cisneros told Xinhua that both regions share political and
cultural values and views in matters of international policies and
bilateral and multilateral relations, but the EU's practice of
subsidies stands as the biggest disagreement between the two blocs.
</P>
<P>
The Mercosur countries, which are Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay
and Paraguay with Chile and Bolivia as partners, are promoting
ties with Asian countries, especially China, to balance their
relations with other regions of the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0159 </DOCNO>
