<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Star Takes Yugoslav Soccer Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Red Star of Belgrade beat the
Partisan club 4-2 on Saturday to lift the Yugoslav soccer cup.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 fans of both clubs went to watch the grand finale
that saw a 2-2 draw at halftime.
</P>
<P>
The Red Star was the first on the scoreboard with two
unanswered goals while the Partisan, the national champions from
last year, levelled the scoring by the halftime whistle.
</P>
<P>
The hosts, however, managed to score two more goals in the
second half to seal off the victory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Krajicek Crashes out in Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Former champion Richard Krajicek of
the Netherlands has gone out of Wimbledon at the infamous "
champions graveyard" of Court No. 2.
</P>
<P>
But fellow Wimbledon winners Andre Agassi and Boris Becker are
both through to the fourth round, as is multiple finalist Goran
Ivanisevic.
</P>
<P>
Court No. 2, which has accounted for so many top seeds over the
years, hosted its latest shock when the Dutch fifth seed fell to
Lorenzo Manta of Switzerland, 6-3, 7-6 (7/5), 4-6, 4-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss is ranked 196th in the world and had never won a
Grand Slam match until this year's Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
Krajicek looked to have overcome a dreadful start to take the
match into a fifth set.
</P>
<P>
But it was the 24-year-old from Winterthur held his nerve to
book a meeting with 11th seed Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the 1996 champion Krajicek, Becker and Agassi
secured their places in the last 16 with convincing victories.
</P>
<P>
Three-time runner-up Ivanisevic is also in the fourth round
after a 7-6 (7-2), 6-4, 7-6 (7/3) over Paul Haarhuis of the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old Becker, a three-time winner at the world's
biggest grasscourt tournament, beat Australian Lleyton Hewitt 6-1,
6-4, 7-6 (7-5) while Agassi overcame the challenge of Alberto
Martin 6-2, 6-0, 2-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
For the German, there is a match with second seed Pat Rafter,
potentially the match of the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
Becker once again demonstrated why he will be remembered as one
of Wimbledon's outstanding players, overwhelming his teenage
opponent with a mixture of guile and power.
</P>
<P>
The only tricky moments for the right-hander came in the
opening game, which went to several deuces, and the final set
which saw a series of breaks before Becker took the tie-break.
</P>
<P>
For Agassi, the 1992 champion, the match saw him lose his first
set of the tournament against the Spaniard Martin.
</P>
<P>
After displaying top form for the first two sets, the 29-year-
old seemed to lose concentration for a moment in the third and
paid the price as his opponent took the set 6-2.
</P>
<P>
A fortuitous net-cord helped Agassi to a vital break in the
seventh game of the next set, and the fourth seed reestablished
control to take the match.
</P>
<P>
Australian qualifier Wayne Arthurs beat 14th seed Tommy Haas of
Germany 7-6, 7-6, 7-6 and will now play Agassi.
</P>
<P>
Todd Martin, the American eighth seed, beat another German Jens
Knippschild 6-7, 6-1, 7-6, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
In the women's draw, third seed Lindsay Davenport cruised
through to the last 16 but Julie Halard-Decugis of France, seeded
11, was beaten by American teenager Alexandra Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
Ninth seed Mary Pierce and unseeded Nathalie Dechy avoided the
fate of compatriot Halard-Decugis. Dechy beat Tatiana Panova of
Russia 6-0, 6-3 while Pierce took out Elena Wagner of Germany 6-3,
6-0.
</P>
<P>
Jelena Dokic, the 16-year-old Australian qualifier who defeated
top seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland in the opening round, will
play Pierce after beating Luxembourg's Anne Kremer 6-7, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990627.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hill Hints at British Farewell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Damon Hill has hinted that he may
retire from Formula One auto racing sooner than planned after his
worst qualifying performance in seven years in French Grand Prix
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old announced earlier this month that he will stop
racing at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
But his worst qualifying performance for seven years in France
on Saturday led him to suggest that he may stop racing after the
British Grand Prix in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The former world champion will only be allowed to compete in
Sunday's French GP at Magny-Cours after Jordan appealed to the
stewards.
</P>
<P>
He originally finished outside the time limit of 107% of the
pole position time, after a fire damaged his car and rain then
made the track slower.
</P>
<P>
But Hill admitted the bad performance was still partly his own
fault, and he apologized to team boss Eddie Jordan.
</P>
<P>
"I'd not want to be in a situation where I'm damaging Eddie's
chances and I'd have to say on today's evidence I'm not helping. I
didn't perform well," he admitted.
</P>
<P>
"I only want to race if I feel I can deliver and frankly I don'
t feel like I'm delivering."
</P>
<P>
Hill made his debut for Brabham at Silverstone, and has not
failed to qualify for a Grand Prix since his days with the
uncompetitive former team.
</P>
<P>
The winner of 22 races would be guaranteed an emotional send-
off from British fans.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not making any definite announcement but anything is
possible," said Hill when asked if the sell-out event would be his
last race.
</P>
<P>
Jordan said on Friday that he expected Hill to stay on until
the end of the year, and that he was welcome to do so.
</P>
<P>
But earlier in the week he told BBC Radio 5 Live that Hill's
career might end sooner than that.
</P>
<P>
And after Saturday's drama he admitted: "We are talking about
the issue and I'm pleased he's thinking about Jordan's position in
the championship.
</P>
<P>
"This situation is one in which Damon and I clearly understand
what is required, " he added.
</P>
<P>
Hill missed out by just 0.003 of a second on making the
qualifying cut-off time in a chaotic and dangerous wet weather
session.
</P>
<P>
He had to use the spare car when broken exhaust sparked a fire
in his race car and the spare suffered a similar fate after the
session.
</P>
<P>
"Today shows the difficulties I've been going through and that'
s why I announced I'm going to retire," said Hill.
</P>
<P>
"I must say those were the worst conditions I have ever
experienced in a qualifying session. It was extremely treacherous,
" he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
