</P>
<P>
Becker once again demonstrated why he will be remembered as one
of Wimbledon's outstanding players, overwhelming his teenage
opponent with a mixture of guile and power.
</P>
<P>
The only tricky moments for the right-hander came in the
opening game, which went to several deuces, and the final set
which saw a series of breaks before Becker took the tie-break.
</P>
<P>
For Agassi, the 1992 champion, the match saw him lose his first
set of the tournament against the Spaniard Martin.
</P>
<P>
After displaying top form for the first two sets, the 29-year-
old seemed to lose concentration for a moment in the third and
paid the price as his opponent took the set 6-2.
</P>
<P>
A fortuitous net-cord helped Agassi to a vital break in the
seventh game of the next set, and the fourth seed reestablished
control to take the match.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 French Open champion Gustavo Kuerten became the first
Brazilian man to reach Wimbledon's fourth round in the Open era.
</P>
<P>
The 11th-seeded Kuerten, who had a lifetime record on grass of
0-4 until this week, swept past qualifier Nenad Zimonjic 6-4, 6-4,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
Rafter confirmed his reputation as one of the favourites for
the title with a straight sets win over Australia Open finalist
Thomas Enqvist.
</P>
<P>
The second seed broke in the Swede's first service game but
Enqvist hit back to set up a tie-break.
</P>
<P>
Enqvist lost touch on service returns in the second set and
Rafter eased through it with two breaks.
</P>
<P>
After a short break for rain, the first of the championships,
Rafter sealed an impressive 7-6 (7-5), 6-2, 6-3 win.
</P>
<P>
Goran Ivanisevic booked his place in the last 16 at the expense
of his bogey man Paul Haarhuis.
</P>
<P>
Ivanisevic edged a tight match 7-6 (7-5), 6-4, 7-6 (7-5) and
battled back after the Dutchman had two points for a double break
in the third set.
</P>
<P>
Gustavo Kuerten demonstrated his newly-found liking for grass
with a confident 6-4, 6-4, 6-2 win over Nenad Zimonjic.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian had gone out in the first round on his two
previous appearances but has conquered his fears in impressive
style this year.
</P>
<P>
Even playing on the infamous Court Two did not faze him as he
dominated against the Yugoslavian qualifier.
</P>
<P>
Zimonjic struggled with his serve, producing nine double faults,
and Kuerten took full advantage.
</P>
<P>
There were also wins for former semi-finalist Todd Martin while
Germany's Tommy Haas crashed out at the hands of Australian
qualifier Wayne Arthurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
