<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Novotna Moves Through after Struggle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Jana Novotna overcame a sluggish
start to see off Maria Antonia Sanchez Lorenzo and set up a fourth
round clash against Nathalie Dechy at Wimbledon on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The defending champion trailed 3-0 and 4-1 in the opening set
before getting her game together.
</P>
<P>
The confidence returned although she needed three set points to
take the set 6-4.
</P>
<P>
The second set was also close until Novotna broke for 4-3 and
took the next two games to wrap up victory.
</P>
<P>
The Jelena Dokic bandwagon is still rolling in the ladies
singles after she made it through to the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
Dokic, conqueror of top seed Martina Hingis in the first round,
set up a meeting with ninth seed Mary Piece in the last 16 after
beating Anne Kremer.
</P>
<P>
The Australian did not have things all her own way against one
of Luxembourg's only class sporting exports.
</P>
<P>
Kremer claimed the first set on a tie-break but Dokic showed
her growing maturity in taking the next two.
</P>
<P>
US Open champion Lindsay Davenport booked her fourth round
place with a comfortable win over Laura Golarsa, the oldest
survivor in the women's draw.
</P>
<P>
The third seed, still seeking her first Wimbledon title, was
again in composed form with her booming baseline shots again
proving decisive.
</P>
<P>
Davenport assumed control when she won six games in a row to
take the first set and go 4-0 up in the second.
</P>
<P>
Golarsa had no answer as the American wrapped up a 6-3 6-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
Mary Pierce outclassed Elena Wagner with a powerful display on
Court Three to ease into the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchwoman was always in charge of the baseline battle and
her opponent's frustration grew as the match began to drift away
from her.
</P>
<P>
Wagner's serve fell to pieces at times in the second set and
Pierce picked her off at will.
</P>
<P>
She also executed two delightful drop shots near the end of the
second set as she secured a 6-3 6-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon debutante Alexandra Stevenson marched into the last
16 with an impressive straight sets win over 11th seed Julie
Halard-Decugis.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old, who made the Edgbaston quarter-finals earlier
this month, never looked back after taking the first three games
and won 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
The consistent Nathalie Dechy also went through after ending
the giant-killing run of Tatiana Panova.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchwoman was never in trouble on course to her 6-0, 6-3
victory.
</P>
<P>
Last year's runner-up Nathalie Tauziat made short work of Seda
Noorlander as she became the first woman to reach the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
The eighth seed, opening proceedings on Court 13, took command
from the start against the Dutch woman who was making her first
third round appearance.
</P>
<P>
Tauziat held all her service games although Noorlander failed
to take advantage of a number of second serves.
</P>
<P>
The French woman easily progressed with a 6-1, 6-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
Former champion Conchita Martinez saw her latest bid for a
second title end in disappointing fashion as she lost to Lisa
Raymond in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
Martinez lifted the famous trophy in 1994 but has since slipped
from a career-high ranking of second to 20th.
</P>
<P>
The Spaniard played well at the net but struggled with her
first serve as she lost 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Fourteenth seed Barbara Schett carried on her best-ever run at
Wimbledon with a 6-2, 6-3 defeat of Larisa Neiland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
