<HEADLINE> Russian Military Plane Lands at Pristina Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A Russian military plane landed
on Saturday in Pristina, capital town of the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo, as an advancement for the country's peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
The cargo plane, the first to land in Pristina since March 24
when NATO launched air strikes against the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia, carried 21 paratroopers, 18 liaison officers as well
as electronic equipment to Pristina.
</P>
<P>
The Russians will deal with the air traffic at the Pristina
airport which is to be used by all peacekeeping troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A French military cargo plane landed in Pristina later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
Russia will send some 3,610 troops to Kosovo and they would
remain there until mid June 2000 as part of the international
presence.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who ordered the dispatch, also
instructed to send in 210 police officers and 30 border guards to
take part in the international police presence in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
